1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,025
Welcome to Lesson 7.

2
00:00:02,025 --> 00:00:07,275
In this lesson, we're going to look at other adaptations of bivariate plots.

3
00:00:07,275 --> 00:00:12,000
Let's start by importing the libraries we're going to need,

4
00:00:12,000 --> 00:00:17,295
as well as our fuel economy dataset and extracting our transmission type.

5
00:00:17,295 --> 00:00:20,580
To add color to most seaborne plots,

6
00:00:20,580 --> 00:00:24,375
we can just provide this new parameter called hue.

7
00:00:24,375 --> 00:00:27,780
For example, if we look at a point plot and plot

8
00:00:27,780 --> 00:00:32,790
the combined vehicle highway city efficiency versus vehicle class,

9
00:00:32,790 --> 00:00:36,655
we can then also segment by transmission type.

10
00:00:36,655 --> 00:00:38,210
Using this point plot,

11
00:00:38,210 --> 00:00:40,865
we can end up getting something like this.

12
00:00:40,865 --> 00:00:44,180
This hue parameter is common for most seaborne plots.

13
00:00:44,180 --> 00:00:49,270
We can create similar plots for a clustered bar chart.

14
00:00:49,270 --> 00:00:51,875
This is an adapted cluster bar chart.

15
00:00:51,875 --> 00:00:55,010
The only difference is now instead of a point plot,

16
00:00:55,010 --> 00:00:58,775
we're passing in bar plot with the hue parameter.

17
00:00:58,775 --> 00:01:03,185
Similarly, we can create a similar comparison using

18
00:01:03,185 --> 00:01:07,490
the box plot function to create a clustered box chart.

19
00:01:07,490 --> 00:01:10,850
Once again, our x-variable is vehicle class,

20
00:01:10,850 --> 00:01:13,550
our y is combined fuel efficiency,

21
00:01:13,550 --> 00:01:16,535
and our hue is transmission type.

22
00:01:16,535 --> 00:01:20,945
I have also added rotation for the x-label,

23
00:01:20,945 --> 00:01:24,755
15 degrees to make it easier to view.

24
00:01:24,755 --> 00:01:27,710
We can also adapt heatmaps,

25
00:01:27,710 --> 00:01:29,675
that is 2D histograms,

26
00:01:29,675 --> 00:01:32,840
so that instead of color being based on count,

27
00:01:32,840 --> 00:01:37,160
color is based on the average of a third variable.

28
00:01:37,160 --> 00:01:44,555
Let's start by plotting a 2D histogram of combined efficiency versus engine displacement.

29
00:01:44,555 --> 00:01:47,900
Color is going to be the total number of counts.

30
00:01:47,900 --> 00:01:52,580
I'm going to set a minimum threshold for a cell to be colored to

31
00:01:52,580 --> 00:01:57,450
be 0.5 and I'm going to choose my color palette.

32
00:01:57,450 --> 00:02:00,530
Here we have our 2D histogram of

33
00:02:00,530 --> 00:02:05,390
a fuel efficiency versus displacement where each bin shows the number of counts.

34
00:02:05,390 --> 00:02:12,200
Let's now change this so that color shows the average CO2 output for each bin.

35
00:02:12,200 --> 00:02:16,595
This uses the weight parameter of the hist 2D function.

36
00:02:16,595 --> 00:02:23,420
By default, each points weight is worth one so that the colors reflect the total counts.

37
00:02:23,420 --> 00:02:26,270
If we change it so that each points weight is equal to

38
00:02:26,270 --> 00:02:30,380
its CO2 emissions divided by the number of cars in that bin,

39
00:02:30,380 --> 00:02:34,145
then the total within each bin will be the average.

40
00:02:34,145 --> 00:02:36,635
Let's break this into steps.

41
00:02:36,635 --> 00:02:41,270
Our first step is to figure out in which bin each point falls.

42
00:02:41,270 --> 00:02:45,035
We compute this using the pandas cut function.

43
00:02:45,035 --> 00:02:50,255
We pass in the series or the array from the DataFrame,

44
00:02:50,255 --> 00:02:57,385
the bin sizes and then we have to recast that to ensure it's an integer.

45
00:02:57,385 --> 00:03:01,940
Next, we count up the points that fall in each bin.

46
00:03:01,940 --> 00:03:05,090
We do this by using a group by statement over

47
00:03:05,090 --> 00:03:10,685
both the engine size and efficiency bin sizes.

48
00:03:10,685 --> 00:03:19,160
Then we use the pivot method to then group that into one, two-dimensional array.

49
00:03:19,160 --> 00:03:25,540
Finally, we use the values attribute to get the number of points as an array.

50
00:03:25,540 --> 00:03:29,150
Now, we can get our point weights using all of these values.

51
00:03:29,150 --> 00:03:33,485
We take the CO2 series and divide each element

52
00:03:33,485 --> 00:03:38,590
by the number of points in each bin just right here.

53
00:03:38,590 --> 00:03:45,640
We can now pass this to the weights parameter of our 2D hist function.

54
00:03:45,640 --> 00:03:51,065
What we see here is pretty clear that as engine size gets larger,

55
00:03:51,065 --> 00:03:58,320
efficiency goes down, which also means the emissions go up drastically.

